            <h2 id="add-sale">2) Add a sale</h2>
            
            <h3 id="function-objective">2.1) Function objective</h3>
            <p>The Add a sale section allows creating a new commercial transaction with a customer. It constitutes one of the most central functions of Movelys, as it records:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>The sale content (products/services),</li>
                <li>Commercial terms (discounts, taxes, payments),</li>
                <li>Customer relations (new or existing),</li>
                <li>And operational impacts (inventory, invoices, reports, etc.).</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3 id="interface-presentation">2.2) Interface presentation</h3>
            <p>The interface consists of functional Sections which are:</p>
            
            <h4>‚ùñ The General sale information section:</h4>
            <p>It groups the key administrative elements of a transaction, those that define the <strong>sale framework which are:</strong></p>
            
            <h5>1. Customer</h5>
            <p>This field allows <strong>linking the sale to an existing customer in the database, or adding a new customer if necessary.</strong> This enables:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Tracking their purchase history,</li>
                <li>Generating personalized invoices,</li>
                <li>Managing specific commercial terms (discounts, deferred payment, etc.).</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Why it's important:</strong> Without customer identification, it's impossible to manage credit, send personalized receipts, or retrieve the sale later.</p>
            
            <h5>2. Payment term (or payment deadline)</h5>
            <p>Optional field to define in <strong>how many days the payment should be made.</strong> Examples:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>0 days (cash payment),</li>
                <li>15 days (Net 15),</li>
                <li>30 days (Net 30),</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This activates credit management and helps the system track customer receivables and reminders.</p>
            
            <h5>3. Sale date</h5>
            <p>This is the date when the transaction is recorded (or supposed to occur). By default, Movelys suggests the current date, but it can be modified for:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>A retroactive order,</li>
                <li>An administrative postponement.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This date is used in accounting, sales reports, and fiscal reports.</p>
            
            <h5>4. Billing scheme</h5>
            <p>Term used to designate the <strong>automatic or manual invoice numbering model.</strong> A billing scheme can be:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Standard (for example: INV-2025-001),</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Customized (by customer or sale type),</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p>It allows organizing invoices in a uniform and traceable manner.</p>
            
            <h5>5. Invoice number</h5>
            <p>Unique number identifying the sale (or draft) in the system. It can be:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Automatically generated by the system following the scheme,</strong></li>
                <li>Or manually entered by the user (if authorized).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This number is crucial for archiving, legal invoicing, and accounting tracking.</p>
            
            <h5>6. Attach a document</h5>
            <p>Option to add an attached file to the sale. Examples:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Customer purchase order,</li>
                <li>Advance payment proof,</li>
                <li>Specific commercial terms,</li>
                <li>External invoice or signed quote.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Supported formats are typically: PDF, CSV, DOCX, PNG.</p>
            <p>Useful to justify a sale or attach any contractual document related to this transaction.</p>
            
            <h4>Summary: What is this section for?</h4>
            <p>The "General Information" section allows to:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Precisely identify the sale and concerned customer,</li>
                <li>Define the legal and commercial framework of the transaction,</li>
                <li>Ensure data consistency across the entire Movelys system.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>‚ùñ Product addition section</h4>
            <p>In this section you can add a product and also search for a product already present in the database to add it to the table</p>
            
            <h4>‚ùñ Sale parameters section</h4>
            <p>It groups fields used to adjust pricing conditions, apply discounts, manage taxation, and insert internal or customer notes about the sale.</p>
            
            <h5>1. Discount type</h5>
            <p>This field defines how the discount is applied to the sale. The most common types are:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Percentage (%): proportional reduction (e.g. 10%)</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Fixed amount: absolute value reduction (e.g. 5,000 FCFA)</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p>It determines how the discount will be calculated on the total amount or on each item.</p>
            
            <h5>2. Discount amount</h5>
            <p>This field specifies the amount or percentage of discount to apply according to the chosen type. Examples:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>If the type is %, entering "10" will apply a 10% reduction on the order.</li>
                <li>If the type is amount, entering "2000" will deduct 2000 FCFA from the gross total.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Allows offering customer benefits or applying commercial policies (sales, promotions, commercial gestures).</p>
            
            <h5>3. Order tax rate (sometimes called 'Order Tax' or 'Order VAT')</h5>
            <p>This is the tax rate applied to the entire order. It is defined:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Either automatically according to the country or default configuration (e.g. 18%),</li>
                <li>Or selected manually (if multiple rates are possible depending on products or customers).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This rate is used for automatic VAT calculation or any regulatory tax, and will be included in the invoice.</p>
            
            <h5>4. Sale note</h5>
            <p>Free text field to add textual information to the sale. Usage examples:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Special instruction for delivery or billing,</li>
                <li>Specific commercial condition,</li>
                <li>Mention of a verbal agreement or customer commitment,</li>
                <li>Internal note for colleague follow-up.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This note may appear on the customer ticket, invoice, or remain internal depending on configuration.</p>
            
            <h4>Summary: Role of this section</h4>
            <p>The "Sale Parameters" section is essential to:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Customize pricing conditions,</li>
                <li>Comply with tax regulations,</li>
                <li>Facilitate internal or customer communication.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>It gives the seller controlled negotiation flexibility while maintaining complete traceability.</p>
            
            <h4>‚ùñ Shipping and logistics information section</h4>
            <p>It groups all elements necessary for order preparation, shipping, delivery, and <strong>physical tracking.</strong> It is activated as soon as a product needs to be physically delivered to the customer.</p>
            
            <h5>1. Shipping details</h5>
            <p>Global field used to:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Briefly describe shipping methods,</li>
                <li>Indicate a tracking number,</li>
                <li>Mention a specificity (e.g.: express, grouped, by appointment...).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Serves as a visible summary for the seller or logistics.</p>
            
            <h5>2. Delivery address</h5>
            <p>Exact address where products should be delivered. It can be:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Selected from the customer record (saved address),</li>
                <li>Entered manually (temporary or different address).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This address is mandatory if delivery is planned. It is used for documents, labels, and zone calculations.</p>
            
            <h5>3. Shipping fees</h5>
            <p>Amount to charge the customer to cover transport or shipping costs. This field can be:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Entered manually,</li>
                <li>Or calculated automatically by an external module (zones, weight, carrier).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The amount is added to the order's total including tax.</p>
            
            <h5>4. Shipping status</h5>
            <p>Current logistics status of the order. Examples:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Not shipped,</li>
                <li>Pending delivery,</li>
                <li>In transit,</li>
                <li>Delivered,</li>
                <li>Cancelled.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This status evolves with logistics tracking. It is crucial for customer service, traceability, and reminders.</p>
            
            <h5>5. Delivered to</h5>
            <p>Name of the person receiving the order at the delivery address. This field is useful if the recipient is not the initial customer (e.g.: assistant, receptionist, third-party company).</p>
            <p>This avoids reception errors or confusion on site.</p>
            
            <h5>6. Delivery person</h5>
            <p>Name or identifier of the person in charge of order delivery. It can be:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>An internal employee (logistics),</li>
                <li>A partner carrier,</li>
                <li>Or an external company</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This field facilitates responsibility tracking and potential claims.</p>
            
            <h5>7. Shipping documents</h5>
            <p>Files related to delivery: delivery note (DN), carrier slip, proof of receipt, etc. Accepted formats: PDF, images, Excel, Word...</p>
            <p>These documents ensure <strong>delivery proof, complete administrative and legal tracking.</strong></p>
            
            <h5>Button: Add additional expenses</h5>
            <p>This button allows recording <strong>expenses associated with the order but not billed to the customer.</strong> Expense examples:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Packaging costs,</li>
                <li>Handling,</li>
                <li>Transport commission,</li>
                <li>Purchase of shipping-related accessories.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h5>What is it for?</h5>
            <ul>
                <li>To track the real profitability of the order,</li>
                <li>Allocate these costs in analytical accounting,</li>
                <li>Manage a journal of logistics expenses per sale.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>These expenses don't impact the customer total but enrich <strong>internal</strong> cost reports.</p>
            
            <h4>Role of this section</h4>
            <p>The logistics section enables <strong>complete management of the delivery chain, from address entry to post-delivery tracking.</strong> It is indispensable for any business performing <strong>physical deliveries, as it:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Guarantees traceability,</li>
                <li>Optimizes logistics costs,</li>
                <li>Facilitates communication between teams (sales, inventory, transport).</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>‚ùñ Payment details section</h4>
            <p>This section allows recording the <strong>exact financial terms related to a transaction.</strong> It is crucial to ensure <strong>accounting traceability, proper cash flow management, and</strong> the <strong>consistency of financial reports.</strong></p>
            
            <h5>1. Quantity</h5>
            <p>In the context of a payment, this field can have several meanings depending on the form type.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>If the payment is linked to several sold items, the quantity corresponds to the number <strong>of invoiced items (often automatic from the products section).</strong></li>
                <li>In a <strong>staggered payment form, this field can indicate the number of</strong> <strong>partial payments recorded or allowed.</strong></li>
                <li>In a <strong>partial or multi-mode payment context, it can represent the</strong> <strong>quantity of</strong> <strong>products covered by a deposit.</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Ensure the paid amount corresponds to one or several precise product quantities, or payment steps.</p>
            
            <h5>2. Payment method</h5>
            <p>The payment method defines how the customer settles the transaction. The most common options include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Cash:</strong> Payment in cash.</li>
                <li><strong>Bank transfer:</strong> Payment made by transfer from a bank account.</li>
                <li><strong>Credit card:</strong> Payment via electronic payment terminal (POS).</li>
                <li><strong>Check:</strong> Deferred payment by paper check.</li>
                <li><strong>Customer credit:</strong> Payment at a later due date (customer debtor account).</li>
                <li><strong>Mobile payment:</strong> Ex.: Orange Money, Moov Money, MTN Mobile Money...</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Allow the company to track financial flows by method, useful for accounting, cash register, audits, and refunds.</p>
            
            <h5>3. Payment note</h5>
            <p>The payment note is a free field intended to enter any additional information <strong>or justification related to the financial transaction.</strong> Examples:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>"Deposit paid by transfer, balance expected within 7 days."</li>
                <li>"Payment by two different people."</li>
                <li>"Partial payment, discount pending."</li>
                <li>"Reduced amount following an exceptional commercial discount."</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Keep a written record to better explain certain payment operations, avoid disputes, and facilitate accounting verifications.</p>
            
            <h5>4. Payment date</h5>
            <p>This is the effective date when the payment was made or recorded in the system. Two scenarios:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>If payment is immediate: this date is often equal to the sale or invoice date.</li>
                <li>If payment is deferred or staggered: this date is chosen manually and can be future or past (in case of regularization).</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> This date is used for:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Sales or cash flow reports by period,</li>
                <li>Establishing payment schedules,</li>
                <li>Reminders in case of pending payment.</li>
            </ul>
            
